skeletonlisp
Class PrimitiveApplier

java.lang.Object
  skeletonlisp.PrimitiveApplier

public class PrimitiveApplier
extends java.lang.Object

PrimitiveApplier is used to evaluate applications whose procedure is a primitive.

PrimitiveApplier consists mostly of the algorithmic methods for each of the SkeletonLisp's primitive keywords.

Since all the arguments of an application are given in a list form, even primitives like ADD1 and SUB1, that take only one argument, get their argument in a list form.

lookupPrimitive

public LExp lookupPrimitive(LId proc)
                     throws java.lang.Exception
The method lookupPrimitive() can be used to check whether a given keyword is a primitive or not.

Parameters:
proc - proc is the procedure of an application
Returns:
the procedure itself is returned if it is a primitive
Throws:
java.lang.Exception - throws an Exception if the procedure is not a primitive.

The method list() (primitive LIST) takes any number of non-pre-evaluated arguments. It returns a new list with all the arguments evaluated in the same order that the original arguments were given to LIST.

Parameters:
args - the list of arguments given to LIST

Throws:
java.lang.Exception - An exception is thrown if, for some reason, any of the arguments cannot be evaluated.
